{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/0027955887A/1945113001/0393.xml":{"full_text":"Served By Leased Wire*\nof the\nUNITED PRESS\nand the\nASSOCIATED PRESS\nWith Complete Coverage of\nState and National New*\nVOL779.-NO. 17. WILMINGTON, N. C., FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 30. 1945 ESTABLISHED 1867\n_-\u2014 -:_*___\nPolice Hold\nLines Open\nFor Workers\nAT HIGGINS PLANT\nOfficer* Appear With Tear\nGas, Machine Guns As\nWork Resumes\n<rrW ORLEANS, Nov. zy\u2014tU.RJ\u2014\npolice appeared at Higgins Indus\ntries tndav armed with machine\nsuns tear' gas and riot weapons,\nL they had no use for them as\nnearly 100 workers crossed a\ndoubled AFL picket line to rejoin\nthe industrial forces of Andrew J.\nHiggins.\nHe was rehinng men to complete\nin undisclosed number of contracts\n*0W on hand. Higgins would not\n6 how many would be employed,\nand shunned questions as to the\namount of work that will be done\nby these men.\nOnly several minor outbreaks oc\ncurred during this first day of re\nhiring at the multi-million dollar\nHiggins company which was plac\ned in liquidation following a drawn\nout fight with the unions by its\npresident.\nA plumbing supply truck at\ntempted to cross the union\u2019s line,\nI but the pickets halted the vehicle.\nPolice told the driver to disregard\nthe pickets\u2019 warning, \u201cIf you drive\nthat truck across that line, we\u2019ll\nturn it over,\u201d but the chauffeur\ndecided against it.\nAll of the men hired today were\nreported to have worked for Hig\ngins before he closed the plants\nNjv. 1 in tlfe midst of a strike by\n3,500 members of the AFL New\nOrleans Metal Trades Council.\nMany of the men admitted they\nwere union members, and a hand\nful were discharged servicemen\nwith overseas records. One Paci\nfic veteran commented, \u201ca man\u2019s\ngot to eat.\u201d i\nAFL spokesman Norman De La-\npauyade declared that the union is\nmaintaining its original stand in\nregard to the contractual demands\nwhich Higgins has refused to meet\n\"We are willing to go to work\nas soon as Mr. Higgins signs a 1\ncontract,\u201d De Lapouyade said.\nThe union demands involved five 1\npoints, foremost among them that 1\nreturning servicemen must join up,\nand that foremen should be union\nmembers. 1\nAt the time of liquidation, it was 1\ndisclosed that the company held\ncontracts totaling ^>5,000,000. Hig-\ngins had said previously that he\nhad orders and contracts for $40,\n000.000 worth of post war marine I\nand building material products. i\nNAZI OVERLORDS i\nSEE H( )R FILM,\nNUERNBERG, Nov. 18\u2014(JP)\u2014\nTwenty Nazi overlords viewed\nfilms of the horrors of German\nconcentration camps with reactions\nranging from tears to curt indif\nference at the Nuernberg war\ncrimes trial today.\nFat Hermann Goering, mirthful\nearlier in the day, sat soberly.\nField Marshal Wilhelm Keitel\nwiped his mouth with a white\nhandkerchief, and stalked quickly\nfrom the courtroom.\nThe one-hour showing of the\nshocking pictures of starved, beat\nen and dead victims of Nazi per\nsecutions followed the reading into\n\u2018he court record of Georing\u2019s\ninreats and exultations in the Nazi\nseizure of Austria in 1938. Georing\nad been convulsed with laughter\nrepeatedly as the transcript of his\nfephone conversations at that\nwas read by the prosecution,\nalther Funk, former Minister\nth ,\u2122nomics> brushed tears from\ne fleshy pockets under his eyes\nas he watched the films.\nnnerved by the show, the form\n5- Governor-General of Poland,\nF?nk\u2019 sat huddled in his\nW thout hfting his head for\n1U mtnutes.\nDeRnm0lft-HeSS\u2019 ihe former No. 2\nalert Fuehrer appearing more\nanv surroundings than on\nccasion since the start of the\nI (C\u00b0ntinued on Page Two; Col. 2)\nWEATHER\n(BvaS|ter\u00ab \u00aetani\u00bbrfl Time)\ni Meteorowi Wtath'r Bureau)\n1 ending0-1 inata for the 24 houra\nndl,\u2019S 7:30 p.m. yesterday\n1:30 a m Temperatures\n7:30 p.m '5246' ,:3\u00b0 a'm- 391 1:30 P-m- 52;\nNwmasjJ1 53; Minimum 38; Mean 45;\n,1:30 a.m 9i. -*I\u201cmid\u201cy\n7:30 P.m 78 7,30 a m- 35; 1:30 p.m. 45;\nTotal f0r ,.p;\u00ab\u2018Pitati\u00bbB\n\u00ab-0O inches. h\u00b0Urs end\u201c8 7 :J0 p.m.\u2014\n(from it, Tides f\u00b0r Today\nU. s. Coast'^f jT^?1cs Published by\nst ana Geodetic Survey)\n\"'Tmingtcn H1GH LOW\n8:38 a.m. 1:13 a.m.\nMasonboro Inlet /a1,pm' 1:38 p.m.\nuuet 4:47 a.m. 10:56 a.m.\ni afsunrise r.=:q 4:56 P*ni. 11:08 p.m.\ni ^\u00b0\u00b0nrise 7-07 a,m,: Sunset 5:03 p.m.;\nHirer star. Mo\u00b0uset 3:01 p.m.\n8 a'\u00bb- Thursday4 l^tet.111'\u2019 C>\noiUinued on Page Two; Col. 4)\nFell 80 Floors, Walks\nAided by crutches, plucky Mrs.\n3etty Lou Oliver, 20, smiles as she\n;akes her first steps into the arms\n5f her husband Navy TorpedomaS\n1-C Oscar L. Oliver at Bellevue\nHospital in Newt York. These are\n:he first steps she has taken since\nler 80-floor fall in an elevator at\n;he time of the Empire State Build\ning-bomber crash four months ago.\nrhe cable on the elevator snapped\nvhen the Army plane hit the New\nfork skyscraper. (International)\nrRUMAN CHEERFUL\nON RECONVERSION\nPresident Says Factories\nOf Nation Are Ahead\nOf Schedule\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 29\u2014 OP)\nPresident Truman reported with a\niheerful smile today that recon\nversion is ahead of schedule.\nHe -read' to his news conference\ni progress report on \u201cthe Jhgt,100\nlays of \u2018reconversion\u201d and com\nnented that the administration\ntas not been asleep.\nIt concluded with the statement\nhat \u201cthe cost of living has de\nfined 0.3 of 1 per cent since the\nurrender of Japan compared with\ni rise of approximately 1.4 per\n:ent in a comparable period after\nhe last war.\u201d\nThe Chief Executive emphasized,\nlowever, that the country is still\nn the midst of reconversion, that\n\u2018inflationary pressures are still\ntreat\u201d and that \u201cwe must con\ninue to hold the line.\u201d\nThe cost of living figure?, he\nlaid, came from the Labor Depart\nnent. The report noted that \u201csome\n>f the decrease is due to the sea\nsonal decrease in some food costs.\u201d\nOn other phases of reconversion,\nhe President reported:\n1. \u201cEmployment in non-war ac\nivities has increased since V-J\nlay. Total employment has now\n\u2022eturned to the V-J day level and\ns expected to continue to rise.\u201d\n2. \u201cThe job of reconverting our\nslants from war to peace is vir\nually completed.\u201d\n3. \u201cOFA has reduced orders and\n\u25a0egulations on its books to 55 from\ni wartime peak of 650. ODT has\nL4 orders standing, as compared\n[Continued on Page Two; Col. 7)\nKINSTON MAN MAY\nSUCCEED J.O. CARR\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 29 (/P)\nnorth Carolina Senators today\nnade several recommendations for\nJ. S. district attorneyships.\nFor the Eastern District Sena\nors Hoey and Bailey recommend\n'd Charles R. Rouse of Kinston,\n;o fill the unexpired term of J.\nJ. Carr, of Wilmington, resigned.\n:ol. John Hall Manning of Raleigh,\ns expected to return socn from\nhe Army to take his old job as\nrssistant district attorney, Hoey\nsaid.\nFor the Middle District recom\nendations include Bryce R. Holt,\n>f Greensboro, to act in the ab\nsence of District Attorney Carlisle\nHiggins of Sparta, on leave to serve\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 3)\nBRITISH SOLDIER\nRINGS 2,015 BELLS\nBUT FINDS SISTER\nBOSTON, Nov. 29.\u2014(IP)\u2014A Bri\ntish soldier of Irish extraction rang\n2,015 doorbells\u2014by his own count\nyesterday looking for his sister,\nMar j.\nThen, he said he decided to call\nupon the Leprechauns\u2014those know\ning little fairies of Irish mytholo\ngy\u2014to aid him in the search.\nGunner Maurice Kennedy, re\ncently released after two and one\nhalf years in a Japanese prison\ncamp, is convinced they did.\nHe finally received a call from\na woman who said she knew a\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 2\n200,OOOJ^an Battle Rebels;\nBritir Radian Troops Take Soerabaja;\nChinese Reds Digging In At Tahushan\n_ J. u\nNationalist\nTroops Halt\nNear Mukden\nSOVIET LIFTS BAN\nChiang\u2019s Forces Assured\nSafe Entry Into Man\nchurian City\nBy SPENCER MOOSA\nCHUNGKING, Nov. 29. \u2014<m\u2014\nNationalist troops were reported\nhalting 90 miles from Mukden to\nday after Russia assured them safe\nentry into the city in the first ma\njor step toward reoccupation of\nManchuria.\nChinese press dispatches said ad\nvanced forces were in Kowpangtze\non the Peiping-Mukden railway 90\nmiles southwest of the city where\nJapan in 1931 stirred up an in\ncident as an excuse for conquest.\nTwenty-five miles northeast up\nthe railway right-of-way, however,\nChinese Communist rivals for the\ncontrol of Manchuria, were digging\nin to resist at Tahushan, another\npress account said.\nHsu Chen, Nationalist-appointed\nchairman for Mukden and its pro\nvince of Liaoning, was reported\nready to leave Peiping when the\nRussians flash the green light for\nthe entry into Mukden.\nThe New Szechwan daily said\nthat in addition to the reported\nRussian agreement to permit Na\ntionalist troops to fly Into Mukden\nand the Manchurian capital of\nChangchun several other outstand\ning questions between Chungking\nand Moscow were near agreement.\nChinese newspapers, meanwhile,\nsplashed the news of the appoint\nment of General Marshall as spe\ncial envoy to replace Ambassador\nPatrick J. Hurley, resigned.\nLt. Gen. Albert C. Wedemeyer,\nU. S. commander in China, told a\npress conference here that Mar\nshall would \u201cmake a survey of the\nsituation and make appropriate\nrecommendations to the President\nconcerning future U. S. assistance\n\u2014or military aid\u2014to China.\u201d\nContrary to reports, Wedemeyer\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 4)\nLOCAL MAN KILLED\nON SOUND ROAD\nJoel Jones, Jr., 32, of Carolina\nBeach died last night enroute to\nJames Walker Memorial hospital\nafter being critically injured in a\nwreck of a car driven by R. H.\nThompson, according to reports\nby Highway Patrol and Deputy\nSheriff.\nThe accident took place about\n9 p. m. on the Greenville Sound\nroad at the Four Oak intersection,\nhalfway between Seagate and Capt.\nSherman\u2019s Service Station.\nThe car was traveling east go\ning 50-60 miles when Thompson at\ntempted to make a left curve high\nway patrolmen said. 'I\u2019he car left\nthe road about 20 ykrds before\nstriking a telephone pole, breaking\nit in two and pulling the butt end\nof the pole up out of the ground\nabout five feet. As the car con\ntinued on about 40 yards, it over\nturned three times.\nJones was .thrown clear of the\ncar at the same time it over\nturned but it came to rest on top of\nhim. The car had to be lifted by\nbystanders to release him.\nJones was rushed to the hospital\nby a highway patrolman and dep\nuty sheriff, dieing on the way.\nThompson and Batson, other oc\ncupants of the car, were rushed t\u00b0\nthe hospital by near-by residents.\nThompson, who was in a semi-con\nscious condition, received lacera\ntions of the forehead, fractured\nright leg and abrasions about the\nbody. Thompson received a severe\nlaceration across the top of his\n(Continued in Page Two; Coi. 3)\nBoston Mayor-Elect At Trial I\nCharged with mail frauds growing out Of what the Government\ndescribed as a \u201cwar contracts brokerage racket\u201d, Mayor-elect James\nM. Curley (above, left) of Boston ic pictured leaving U. S. District\nCourt in Washington with hislawyer, William E. Leahy, shortly after\nhe and four other defendants were put on trial.\n__ (International Soundphoto)\nLrauup roll Declares:\nPublic In Favor\nOf IS Per Cent\nWage Increases\nThirty Per Cent Believed Excessive By Ma\njority On Question Of Extra Pay To\nBolster Loss Of Overtime In Plants\nBy GEORGE GALLUP\nDirector, American Institute of Public Opinion\nPRINCETON, N. J., Nov. 29.\u2014Questioning thousands\nof persons in all parts of the United States reveals the fol\nlowing public thinking in regard to wage increases.\n1\u2014A majority of the voting public opposes pay boosts\nof 30 per cent in hourly rates in former war industries where\nSTAR ADDS GALLUP\nPOLL TO FEATURES\nComplete News Reports Of\nInstitute To Be Carried\nFour Days Weekly\nBeginning today the Wilmington\nStar will expand its coverage of\nnational news by offering the read\ners the complete news reports of\nthe American Institute of Public\nOpinion, known from coaSt to\ncoast as the Gallup Poll.\nResults of polls will appear in\nthe Star each Sunday, Wednesday,\nFriday, and Saturday. In being\nelected to membership in the In\nstitute, the Star takes its place\nwith more than 100 American news\npapers which have combined to\nmake possible one of the most im\nportant developments in Journal\nism in recent years.\nNewspapers long ago achieved a\nthorough and systematic method\nContinued on Page Two; Col. 4)\nworkers nave sunerea a isu per\ncent average decrease in take\nhome pay because of a reduction\nin working hours after the war.\nHowever, while a majority con\ntinues to oppose the 30 per cent\nraise, there has been a slight in\ncrease, in the number favoring the\nboost. Whereas last month 33 per\ncent believed this increase justified\nin former war industries, today\nthe figure favoring such an in\ncrease is 38 per cent.\nThe majority continues to feel\nthat a 30 per cent increase is ex\ncessive.\n2\u2014 Although the majority op\nposes an increase of as much as\n30 per cent, most voters are pre\npared to see some increase grant\ned. In addition to the 38 per cent\nwho would favor a 30 per cent\nraise, another 31 per cent who did\nnot favor this increase said they\nwould favor a pay boost of 15 per\ncent, making a total of more than\ntwo opt of every three favoring an\nincrease of at least 15 per cent.\n3\u2014 As reported in an earlier sur\nvey, a majority of voters wijh\nopinions on the subject think that\nprices of automobiles will have to\nbe increased if a wage boost of\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 6) s\nNew Battles i\nReported In\nJava Cities\nSITUATION TENSE\nLocal Administration Op\nerating In Great Naval\nBase Areas\nBATAVIA, Java, Nov. 29\u2014UP\u2014\nindian forces have completely oc\ncupied Soerabaja after a bloody\n[9-day battle in the great naval\ncase, and a local administration\ns operating under British control,\nhe British command announced\noday.\nAction continued south of Soer\nibaja, and new fighting broke out\nn Batavia. In Bandoeng, summer\ncapital 75 miles southeast of Ba\nca vir, where a British ultimatum\niar ordered all Indonesians out\njf the northern half of the city by\ncoon today, the situation remained\ntense.\nMeanwhile an official British\npress statement said that the Brit\nish had used Japanese troops and\ntanks in \u201cdefensive\u201d action against\n[he Indonesians in a factory area\naorth of Bandoeng, and that the\n.ise of Japanese troops in Sema\nrang earlier could be similarly\nclassified.\nIn the Bandoeng action a mixed\nforce of Gurkha riflemen, Japanese\ntanks and armored fighting ve\nlicles attacked a factory, and the\nBritish admitted that it was a\nquestion of interpretation of the\nword \u201cdefensive.\u201d\nIndians and Amboinese troops\noattled the Indonesians at Bando\neng in a day-and-night exchange\njf sporadic gunfire, but the Brit\nish said in general the situation\nLX7a< nniet.\nThe British ultimatum directing\nall Indonesians to leave certain\nareas of Bandoeng under penalty\nof being shot was broadcast by\nIndonesian Minister of Information\nAmir Sjar-Fuddin. The British said\nthey were no longer in contact\nwith Soetardjo \u201cgovernor\u201d of west\nJava, who had asked for a truce.\nAh earlier British communique\nsaid Soetardjo had been very hard\nto cooperate, but that his efforts\nwere proving ineffectual because\nhe lacked control over the more\nviolent elements in the Indonesian\nranks.\nGunfire rattled in the Kramat\nsector of BataVia only a few blocks\nfrom the heart of the city when\nIndonesians fired upon the Indian\ntroops on patrol. Amboinese en\ncamped in the area joined the In\ndians in returning fire, but with\ndrew when the British informed\nthem it was not their fight.\nJUDGE HANDS ADVICE\nTO HUSBANDS ABOUT\nWORK AROUND HOME\nFRANKFORT, Ky\u201e Nov. 29\u2014<J\u00a7\n\u2014Circuit Judge Chester D. Adams\ntoday advised husbands to think\ntwice before being too solicitious\nbf their wives\u2019 welfare.\n^he jurist offered his advice att\nar* reading a divorce petition al\nleging cruel and inhumane treat\nment and finding that the wife\u2019s\nbnly charges were that hen. hus\nband insisted on preparing her\nbath, even to fixing the tempera\nture of the water, and on getting\ntinner and doing most of the house\nwork when she came home after\na day of office work.\n.\u201cI took it home and read it to\nmy wife, the jurist said. \u201cI told\nler I feared I was doing too much\nwork around home and begged as\nsurance she wouldn\u2019t divorce me.\u201d\n'DIABETIC STEALS SUGAR\nBOSTON, Nov. 29. (JP) A\nman wha told police he was a dia\nbetic was arrested today on a lar\n:eny charge. He was accused of\n;ealing seven bags of sugar.\nFur Flies From Fala In Skirmish With Blaze\nOn Lawn Of His Late Master\u2019s New York Estate\nRHINEBECK, N. Y\u201e Nov' 25\u2014\n(JP)\u2014That former White House\nfavorite, Fala, was a surgical case\nin a dog hospital today, his usual\nphotogenic appearance marred by\ndeep slashes received in a fight\nwith Elliott Roosevelt\u2019s bull Mas\ntiff, Blaze.\nFala, the little Scottie who was\nthe late President Roosevelt\u2019s pet,\nwas admitted to Dr. Thomas Shel-\ndon\u2019s, hospial last Saturday. Sev- i\neral stitches were required to close 1\nhis wounds and he was weak from\nloss of blood.\nThe middle-aged Fala, who be- j\ncame the father of two pups last 1\nMarch, was a visitor at the Roose-\nvelt family\u2019s Hyde Park estate on\nSaturday. He had been living with 1\nMiss Margaret Suckley, a cousin\n>f the late President, in Rhine\n>eck.\nWhile ambling across a lawn\nrala met the 135-pound Blaze. One\n;rowl ted to another and soon the\nur began to fly\u2014from Fala.\nHaze' was uninjured.\nThe big Mastiff made headlines\nast January when three service\nmen were \"bumped off\" a plane\nbecause they had no travel priority\nas did the dog.\nBlaze then was en route to El\nliot Roosevelt\u2019s wife, actress Faye\nEmerson.\nFala\u2019s condition today was re\nported as good. He will be sent\nhome Sunday as a convalescent.\nj\nu\nFaces! Court-Martial f;\nt r\nl\nI_mKBmmm '41 j\nCommander of the heavy cruiser\nIndianapolis, which was lost in the\nPhilippine Sea July 30, Capt.\nCharles B. McVay, III, 47, faces a\ngeneral court-martial in Washing\nton, under an order issued by the\nNavy Department. The Indianap\nolis, which suffered a casualty list\nof 1,196, was torpedoed after de\nlivering a cargo of atomic bomt\nmaterials to Guam. (International)\nFULL PRODUCTION\nORDERED IN JAPAN\nMacArthur Directive De\nmands Civilian Goods\nMaunf acture\nBy C; R. CUNNINGHAM\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nTOKYO, Nov. 29\u2014Gen Douglas\nMacArthur today ordered Japanese\nbusinessmen to resume essential\ncivilian goods production as quiek\nly as possible, and told the Jap\nanese House of Peers to keep its\ndoors open to the press at all\nsessions.\nMacArthur\u2019s reconversion order\ncame as a Socialist member of the\nJapanese Diet charged that the\ngovernment was dealing secretly\nwith occupation officials on food\nimports and warned that the people\nwere \u201crestive\u201d over the food situa\ntion.\nA headquarters directive told\nJapanese producers to \u201cstimulate\nand encourage immediate, maxi\nmum production of all essential\nconsumers\u2019 commodities, including\nindustrial, agricultural and fish\neries products, and commodities\nneeess&ry for the production of\nsuch essential consumers\u2019 goods.\u201d\nJapanese manufacturers have\nbeen slow to begin production, ap\nparently doubtful of the full mean\ning of \u201cconversion\u201d and fearful\nthat they would violate the Allied\nheadquarters rule against war\ngoods production if they put into\noperation plants once turning out\nwar materials.\nThe directive assured producers\nthat they will get priority in mate\nrial, fuel, equipment and labor\nneeded to turn out goods which help\nfeed, clothe, and house the Jap\nanese.\nBrig. Gen. Ken R. Dyke, chief\nof the civil information and edu\ncation section, said it was Mac\nArthur\u2019s wish that all House of\nPeers sessions be opened to the\npress.\nThe Japanese upper house has\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 5)\nAMERICA DENIES\nMOSCOW REPORT\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 29. (IP)\nA State Department spokesman\ndenied today reports published in\nMoscow that the United States was\napplying \u201cpressure\u201d on Iran and\nIceland for rights to airbases in\nthose countries.\nThe official said the reports car-:\nried by the Soviet news agency,\nTass, official quoted newspapers\nin Copenhagen and Iran were en\ntirely inaccurate.\nHe said the United States had a\ntreaty'with Iceland regarding the\nair bases in Iceland but the sub\nject of postwar use had not been\nbroached yet by either side. With\nregard to Iran, the spokesman re\nferred to Secretary of State Byrnes\u2019\nrecent announcement that United\nStates troops would withdraw com\npletely from Iran by the first of the\nyear as evidence that no pressure\nwas being applied on that country.\nHe said the United States was giv\ning up the airfield there but might\nnegotiate later for permission for\ncommercial planes to use it,\n\nAzerbaijans\nPushes Back\nFrom Tehran\nRETREAT 80 MILL\"\nArmed Shah Savans Re\nported Massacring Insur\ngent Forces\nTEHRAN, Iran, Nov. 29. (U.RJ\u2014\nMore than 200,000 wild Shan Savan\ntribesmen were reported tonight\nto have taken up arms for the Iran\nian government, threatening the\nrear of revolting Azerbaijan \u201cdem\nocrat\u201d troops marching on Tehran\nand forcing1 them to fall back more\nthan 80 miles.\nThe reports said the Azerbaijan\nians withdrew from Takistan, 92\nmiles northwest of Tehran, to Zen\njan, about 175 miles from the Iran\nian capital.\nThe withdrawal was made to pro\ntect the rear and flanks of the\ncolumn marching on Tehran, which\nis threatened by attack from the\nShah Savan tribesmen in the area\nof Sarab, 70 miles east of Tabriz.\nThe Shah Savan tribesmen, whose\nancestors helped Shah Abbas to win\nvictory over the Turks in the early\n17th century, occupy the remote\ninaccessible mountain areas of\nnortheast Iran.\nThey are known to favor the Iran\nian government against the Azer\nbaijanian independence movement\nbecause they are owners of large\nflocks and herds Which they fear\nthe \u201cdemocrats\u201d may expropriate.\nINSURGENTS MARCH\nON CASPIAN CITY\nTehran, Nov. 29. \u2014(^\u2014Azerbai\njan Insurgents, pushing into a\nthird province in northern Iran,\nmarched today on Resht near the\nCaspian Sea, an Iranian communi\nque declared.\nThe bulletin said a small force of\nInsurgents had turned eastward in\ntheir march down the main rail\nline leading toward Tehran, and\nwere advancing on Resht. 15 miles\nfrom the Caspian, in Gilan pro\nvince.\nThe insurgents occupied and then\nevacuated the town of Takistan be\nfore swinging toward the sea, the\ncommunique added.\nResht is 70 miles northwest of\nKazvin, where four battalions of\nIranian troops sent northward to\nward Azerbaijan province were\nhalted last week by a Soviet com\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 2)\n\u201cIKE\u201d BIDS ADIEU\nTO U. S. TROOPS\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 29 (JP)\nGen. Dwight D. Eisenhower, who\nled the Allies in victory in Europe,\nsent this farewell message today\nto American troops who served\nwith him:\n\u201cTo each of you\u2014good-by, good\nluck, and my undying thanks.\u201d\nThe lanky Kansan, known as\n\u201cIke\u201d to GI\u2019s who followed him in\nNorth Africa, through France and\nthe low countries to Germany, had\nintended to return to Europe for\na last visit before assuming his\nduties as Army chief of staff.\nCircumstances, however, have\nprevented this, he said, adding\nthat he would always regret that\nhe could not give \u201ca personal\ngood-by to as many thousands of\nyou as I could meet-\u201d\nEisenhower is in a hospital at\nWhite Sulphur Springs, W. Va.,\nrecuperating from a severe cold.\nThe text of his farewell message\nwas issued by the War Depart\nment.\nThe mesage sent to Gen. Joseph\nT. McNamey, who succeeded\nEisenhower as American com\nmander in Europe, was addressed\n(Continued on Page Two; Col. 3)\nSHOPPING\nDAYS 5HC","height":"27188","width":"20388"}}
